      <hedline>
        <hl1>A 5-Year-Old's Life: Work and Play</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Anne Martin letter comments on Oct 23 article on kindergartens that are introducing children to academic subjects</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Time for Napping in Today's Kindergarten'' (front page, Oct. 23):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No Time for Napping in Today's Kindergarten'' (front page, Oct. 23):</p>
        <p>My years as a kindergarten teacher have shown me that young children don't learn only from assigned tasks and pencil and paper work.</p>
        <p>All the traditional kindergarten activities -- blocks, clay, singing, painting, nature study, story time, dramatic play, playground recess -- may be termed play, but they contain the essential seeds of learning. When children are kept busy with adult-devised curriculums that leave no time or scope for children's lively curiosity about the world, then schools are in effect shutting down the most effective paths to a lifelong involvement with learning.</p>
        <p>ANNE MARTIN  Newton Centre, Mass.  Oct. 23, 2000</p>
      </block>
